{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}
'''Baltagiya''' or '''Baltajiya''' ({{lang-arz|البلطجية}} {{IPA-arz|bɑltˤɑˈɡej.jɑ|}}), also Baltaga or Baltaja ({{lang|arz|البلطجة}} {{IPA-arz|bɑlˈtˤɑɡɑ|}}) is an Egyptian word that originally means "[[hatchet man (politics)|hatchet men]]", from {{lang-tr|[[wikt:baltacı|Baltacı]]}}, who were vigorous, disciplined and loyal servants to the [[Ottoman Empire]], but it generally means "[[wikt:goon|goon]]s" or "[[Crime|thug]]s" or "[[gang]]s," who are often hired to attack regime targets.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jacinto|first=Leela|title=Enter the 'baltagiya': Egypt's repression spills out of the torture chambers|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20110207-egypt-torture-human-rights-repression-spills-out-torture-chambers-baltagiya-police|publisher=[[France 24]]|accessdate=13 February 2012|date=9 February 2011}}</ref> Nonpolitical baltagiya gangs appeared in Egypt in the 1980s; in the 1990s the [[Egyptian National Police|Egyptian police]] decided to hire them, "outsourcing coercion to these baltagiya, paying them well and training them to use sexualized brutality (from groping to rape) in order to punish and deter female protesters and male detainees, alike".<ref>{{cite web|last=Amar|first=Paul|title=Why Mubarak is Out|url=http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/516/why-mubarak-is-out-|publisher=[[Jadaliyya]]|accessdate=13 February 2012|date=1 February 2011}}</ref> They gained international media attention when spotted in the fighting in [[Tahrir Square]] during the [[2011 Egyptian Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Francis|first=Thomas|title=Youth Protesters and Street Gangs Clash in Tahrir Square's Tent City|url=http://pulitzercenter.org/articles/tahrir-square-protests-baltagiya-july-fighting-Egypt-revolution|publisher=[[Pulitzer Center on Crisis Reporting]]|accessdate=13 February 2012|date=4 July 2011}}</ref> In the [[Port Said Stadium disaster]] on 1 February 2012, eyewitnesses accused the police of allowing baltagiya in plain clothes into the stadium with weapons and then not intervening to stop the violence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ossenberg|first=Dietmar|title=Geplante Unruhen ("Planned rioting")|url=http://www.zdf.de/ZDFmediathek/beitrag/video/1557586/Ossenberg:-|publisher=ZDF [[heute journal]]|accessdate=13 February 2012|date=1 February 2012}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

