[[Image:Royalswazisungolf.JPG|thumb|Golf at the Royal Swazi Sun, on a misty day]] The '''Royal Swazi Sun Hotel''' is a major entertainment complex in the [[Ezulwini Valley]] of [[Swaziland]]. Founded in 1965, the complex is located 4 hours from [[Johannesburg]] by road. It is home to a casino, a par-72 golf course, and a spa. The hotel features 149 rooms and is known for its luxurious accommodation. Business Insights called the Royal Swazi Sun Hotel the flagship of Sun International's four hotels in the area.<ref>"The making of Africa's Eden." African Business Jan. 1999: 24. Business Insights: Essentials. Web. 20 Nov. 2016.</ref>
It opened in 1965, three years prior to Swaziland's independence. It was the first casino-hotel in the region.<ref name="Lea2006">{{cite book|last=Lea|first=John|title=Tourism and Development in the Third World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xQWKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT24|accessdate=20 November 2016|date=2006-12-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134986750|pages=24–}}</ref> It was important as a major resort in the area that did not adhere to the [[Apartheid]] policies of South Africa.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comment on integration at Royal Swazi Hotel and Casino|publisher=New York Times|date=28 September 1969}}</ref> The casino is considered an important part of the country's foreign exchange and serves 250,000 people a year, primarily from neighboring South Africa and Mozambique as well as Italy, Switzerland and France.<ref name="Cyr2001">{{cite book|last=Cyr|first=Ruth|title=Twentieth Century Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YlhwTte8pbkC&pg=PA485|accessdate=20 November 2016|year=2001|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=9780595189823|pages=485–}}</ref>
The golf course has hosted many professional tournaments, and is the venue for two current [[Sunshine Tour]] events, the [[Royal Swazi Sun Open]] and the [[Lombard Insurance Classic]].
